# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: a-vindication-of-natural-diet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-defence-of-poetry] "**A Defence of Poetry**" is an unfinished essay by Percy Bysshe Shelley written in February and March 1821 that the poet put aside and never completed.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-defence-of-poetry] In 1840, the text was published posthumously in *Essays, Letters from Abroad, Translations and Fragments*.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-defence-of-poetry] Its earliest U.S. publication was by Ginn and Company in Boston in 1891.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-defence-of-poetry] Shelley wrote the essay in response to his friend Thomas Love Peacock's article "The Four Ages of Poetry", which had been published in 1820.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-defence-of-poetry] , I mean to set about an answer to it....
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-defence-of-poetry] It is very clever, but I think, very false.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-defence-of-poetry] Your anathemas against poetry itself excited me to a sacred rage. . . .
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-defence-of-poetry] The text we know as *A Defence of Poetry* was eventually published eighteen years after Shelley's death, after being subjected to some editing by John Hunt and Shelley's wife Mary Shelley, in her *Essays, Letters from Abroad, Translations and Fragments*.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-defence-of-poetry] Shelley's aim was to show that poets establish morality and inspire the legal norms in a civil society, thus creating a foundation for the other institutions of a community.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-defence-of-poetry] , [Shelley] attempts to prove that poets are philosophers; that they are the creators and protectors of moral and civil laws; and that if it were not for poets, scientists could not have developed either their theories or their inventions.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-defence-of-poetry] The mores so created are codified into laws.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-defence-of-poetry] The social function or utility of poets is that they create and maintain the norms and mores of a society.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-defence-of-poetry] ...Shelley was mainly concerned to explain the moral (and thus the social) function of poetry.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-defence-of-poetry] In doing so, he produced one of the most penetrating general discussions on poetry that we have.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-defence-of-poetry] Shelley’s argument for poetry is an important text of English Romanticism.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-defence-of-poetry] Shelley's conclusive remark that "Poets are the unacknowledged legislators of the world" suggests his awareness of "the profound ambiguity inherent in linguistic means, which he considers at once as an instrument of intellectual freedom and a vehicle for political and social subjugation".
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] "**A Dirge**" is a poetic dirge composed by Percy Bysshe Shelley.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] It was published posthumously in 1824 by his wife, Mary Shelley, in the collection *Posthumous Poems*.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] The text has been set to music by Frank Bridge, Charles Ives, Ottorino Respighi, Roy Ewing Agnew, and Benjamin Britten.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] The rhyme scheme of the eight lines is ABAB CCCB.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] The triplet of vain/strain/main in the second half of the poem adds to the sense of the piling up of emotions.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] It also has the effect of slowing down the poem.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] The dominant themes of the poem are isolation, loneliness, and death.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] It is a scene of desolation and despair.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] The wind moans in a grief that cannot be expressed in words; the rain storm billows in vain; the trees are barren and their branches strain under the unceasing onslaught.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] A dirge is a song meant to invoke and express the emotions of grief and mourning that are typical of a funeral.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] Images of nature are used to symbolize the grief he feels, such as the moaning and wild wind, the sullen clouds, the sad storm, the bare woods, the deep caves, and the dreary main.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] He imbues his natural surroundings with anthropomorphic characteristics and qualities to express his grief.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] The nouns are modified by adjectives that give them human attributes and traits to express his own emotions of dreariness and sadness.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] He concludes that the whole world is “wrong” and is grieving.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] Shelley wrote the poem after the deaths of his friend John Keats and his son William who were buried in a cemetery in Rome.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] The untimely death of Keats reopened the floodgates of emotion for Shelley, inevitably leading him to reexperience the sadness and pain he felt for the death of his infant son.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] In the second line, “Grief too sad for song,” Shelley argued that the grief was ineffable, inexpressible in words.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] The last line, “Wail, for the world’s wrong!”, provides a sense of hope and consolation.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-dirge] Rough wind, that moanest loud Grief too sad for song; Wild wind, when sullen cloud Knells all the night long; Sad storm whose tears are vain, Bare woods, whose branches strain, Deep caves and dreary main,— Wail, for the world's wrong!
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] "**A Letter to Lord Ellenborough**" is a pamphlet written in 1812 by Percy Bysshe Shelley in defence of Daniel Isaac Eaton.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Printed in Barnstaple, the essay is approximately 4,000 words in length.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Shelley defended freedom of speech and criticized the sentencing of publisher Daniel Isaac Eaton.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Shelley argued against punishing blasphemous libel maintaining that religious belief is involuntary and that opinions, even if false, should not be prosecuted.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] In the essay, Shelley argues for concepts which were then quite radical, including complete freedom of the press, and a tolerance for all published opinion, even when false.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] The epigraph on the title page is by Tacitus from *The Annals*, Deorum Offensa, Diis curae.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] An offense to the gods is rectified by the gods.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] A speech by the Marquess Wellesley from July 2 in the *Globe* is quoted.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] In the Advertisement, Shelley wrote that he had waited for four months for someone to attack the sentence but when none was forthcoming, he wrote the letter.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] The title arises from the name of the letter's recipient, who directed the jury that convicted Eaton.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Eaton had been tried and found guilty of "blasphemous libel", for being an atheist.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] At the trial before Edward Law, 1st Baron Ellenborough, the Lord Chief Justice of England, what Mark Sandy of the University of Durham has called a "prejudiced jury" convicted Eaton for printing part three of Thomas Paine's *The Age of Reason*.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Daniel Eaton was put on trial in May 1812.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] During the trial, in which he was accused of being an atheist, as well as the aforementioned "blasphemous libel." In defending himself, Eaton claimed that his beliefs were not atheistic, but deistic.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] He attempted to argue that scripture was open to the type of critique that Thomas Paine had leveled in *The Age of Reason*.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Despite the paucity of evidence, on 15 May 1812, the Ellenborough-led jury found Eaton guilty.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] His sentence was severe, including eighteen months in Newgate Prison and a monthly pillorying for the entire term of his sentence.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] The letter was originally printed in 1812 in Barnstaple by W.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Syle, but because they anticipated prosecution, the edition was mostly destroyed, with only 50 copies delivered to London for private distribution.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] It was published in book form in 1859 in the *Shelley Memorials*.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] It was included in *The Prose Works of Percy Bysshe Shelley*, Volume 1, edited by Harry Buxton Forman in 1880, published by Reeves and Turner in London.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] The letter was republished as *Shelley on Blasphemy: Being His Letter to Lord Ellenborough, Occasioned by the Sentence which He Passed on Mr.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Eaton* in 1883 in London by the Progressive Publishing Company.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] The letter was republished in *A letter to Lord Ellenborough: Occasioned by the Sentence Which He Passed on Mr.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-letter-to-lord-ellenborough] Eaton as publisher of the third part of Paine's 'Age of Reason'* in 1894 in London by R.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] Shelley composed *A Philosophical View of Reform* between November, 1819 and 20 May 1820, meant to address political developments in England at that time.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] He advocated non-violence and a moderate response to the repressive measures imposed by the British government.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] One of the events he addressed was the Peterloo Massacre, which occurred on 16 August 1819, in St.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] Peter's Field near Manchester, where a peaceful demonstration seeking parliamentary reform was attacked by militia.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] The bookseller Richard Carlile had been found guilty of blasphemy by a jury in November, 1819 for printing an edition of *The Age of Reason* (1794-6) by Thomas Paine.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] The “Six Acts” had been promulgated in December which placed restrictions on public gatherings and freedom of the press.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] It was during this unstable political period in England in late 1819 when Shelley started writing *A Philosophical View of Reform*.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] 4. abolish tithes, and make all religions, all forms of opinion regarding the origin and government of the universe, equal under the law.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] 5. make justice inexpensive, certain, and speedy, and extend the institution of juries to every possible occasion of jurisprudence.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] Shelley opposed revolution, advocating instead gradual change through non-violence.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] He argued that individual and institutional reform went hand in hand.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] He maintained that poets, writers, and philosophers would stimulate reforms of the social institutions that would benefit everyone in society.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] Shelley informed his publisher Charles Ollier on 19 December 1819 that he sought *A Philosophical View of Reform* "to be an instructive and readable book, appealing from the passions to the reason of men", informing him that he would not finish it "this season".
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] On 26 May 1820 he asked Leigh Hunt if he could find a publisher for the work: "Do you know any bookseller who wd publish for me an octavo volume entitled 'A philosophical View of Reform'.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] Mary Shelley had a transcript made of the manuscript with plans to publish the work.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-philosophical-view-of-reform] The political essay remained unpublished, however, until 1920 when it appeared for the first time in print in an edition published by Humphrey Milford, Oxford University Press, with an introduction and appendix by Thomas William Rolleston.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] It is a foundational essay advocating for vegetarianism, maintaining that a plant-based diet is essential for bodily health, moral virtue, and social justice.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that meat consumption is unnatural, a "slow but certain poison", causing disease, which "pollutes" the body, and leads to vice and depravity.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He prescribes the return to a "natural" vegetable diet.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] This work is regarded as one of the earliest and most fervent defenses of vegetarianism in English literature.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley wrote four essays on the subject of vegetarianism, "A Vindication of Natural Diet" (1813), the note in *Queen Mab*, in a section of "A Refutation of Deism" (1814), and "On the Vegetable System of Diet", which was published posthumously in 1929.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley first experimented with a vegetarian diet while at the University of Oxford according to Thomas Jefferson Hogg.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley began a vegetarian diet on 1 March 1812 along with his first wife Harriet Westbrook.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley began composing the essay in October–November 1812.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley met John Frank Newton during 1812-1813 and influenced his views on vegetarianism.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Historian Keith Thomas has noted that Newton's *Return to Nature* "provided much of the basis" for Shelley's *A Vindication of Natural Diet*.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The work has been republished since 1813, beginning with an abridged version which was published in Boston by March, Capen, and Lyon in an American collection *Vegetable Diet: As Sanctioned by Medical Men, and by Experience in All Ages*, edited by William A.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The essay was reprinted in 1884 in a new edition in London by Frederick Pitman and by John Heywood and the Vegetarian Society in Manchester.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The original title page was reproduced: *A Vindication of Natural Diet.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Being One in a Series of Notes to Queen Mab (A Philosophical Poem).* London: Printed for J.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The new edition featured a preface by Henry Stephens Salt and William Axon.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In 1904, the work was republished in London by C.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Daniel as *A Vindication of Natural Diet and Extracts from the Works of Dr.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley used the imagery of slaughtering a lamb.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In the novel *Frankenstein; or, The Modern Prometheus* (1818), which he is acknowledged to have contributed to, the Being is portrayed as a vegetarian.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The Being explained his vegetarian diet to Victor Frankenstein: "My food is not that of man.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] I do not destroy the lamb and the kid to glut my appetite; acorns and berries afford me sufficient nourishment." Shelley's views on vegetarianism are routinely incorrectly attributed to his wife.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In *Laon and Cythna*, republished as *The Revolt of Islam* (1817), Fifth Canto, the Festival of nations held after the Revolution is a banquet where no meat is served.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The feast is vegetarian: "Never again may blood of bird or beast/ Stain with its venomous stream a human feast".
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] This is "The banquet of the free" where the guests are described as "reclining as they ate, of Liberty,/ And Hope, and Justice".
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The festival was not polluted by gore, "But piled on high, an overflowing store/ Of pomegranates, and citrons, fairest fruit,/ Melons, and dates, and figs, and many a root".
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that eating meat was unnatural.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He maintained that diseases and immorality arose from mankind's "unnatural habits of life".
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] A meatless diet was the best regimen for maintaining a healthy and disease-free lifestyle.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He wrote that human diseases could be decreased by a return to a natural vegetable diet.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley argued that eating meat was a practice that polluted the body with syphilis and resulted in other ailments.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] In *A Vindication of Natural Diet* he wrote, "Should ever a physician be born with the genius of Locke, I am persuaded that he might trace all bodily and mental derangements to our unnatural habits," these unnatural habits being the consumption of meat.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He cited the allegory of Prometheus who stole fire from the gods which enabled mankind to cook meat, thereby screening the disgust and horror of dead flesh.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] He concluded that a person with compassion and empathy for animals, "rising from a meal of roots", would be able to maintain a healthy and balanced diet and lifestyle.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] Shelley presented examples of how a vegetarian diet resulted in longevity and an increased lifespan.
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The only threat of death will be that of natural, old age, that "old age would be our last and our only malady".
[src:a-vindication-of-natural-diet/a-vindication-of-natural-diet] The two rules he prescribes for a natural diet are to never eat anything that was alive and to drink only distilled water.
